<br>
Night fell upon Tir na Nog. Even as the moon approached its zenith, the streets still bustled with the life of a capital town. Every now and then, a cheer would escape this or that tavern. The guardians of the city changed shifts for the last hours of twilight, though they did not expect much to occur in the dead of night. A few crafters remained at the forge this eve, trying to finish their last orders of the day, or work on that favorite project, tirelessly honing their craft. The forges burned bright, casting shadows into every corner of the merchant’s bazaar. <br>
<br>
Shadows that served well as the home for the kindred shade. <br>
<br>
He remained deep within the alley, watching the late night crowd dwindling in number, watched as the city guards grew careless in their patrols, watched as the clouded sky covered the moon for longer periods of time. He would bide his time, he knew the inevitability of this night’s business. He thought it over again and again, trying to convince himself that he saw every angle, knew every action and repercussion, thought of every wrinkle that could develop in his plan. <br>
<br>
With a frustrated grunt, he shook his head clear of the thoughts. The choice had already been made; there was no turning back at this point. With new resolve, the shade moved through the back alleyways, finding little trouble in coming before the building he sought. <br>
<br>
The rogue guildhall looked exactly the same. Even with the business at hand weighing on his mind, the shade could not help but think briefly of the first time he infiltrated this guild headquarters. That time had been much easier, having sent in a decoy through the front, allowing him the chance to enter through a secret window, high above the merchant bazaar. He knew precautions had been put in place since that attack. He toyed with the thought of what another “distraction” from that vicious blademaiden could accomplish this night, but quickly dismissed such impractical thoughts. This was his battle, and his alone. The stakes were much higher this time around, as were the dangers held within. <br>
<br>
As the next cloud made its way over the face of the moon above, the shadow darted across the street, slipping in through the door, and calmly walked through the foyer room. He kept his cloak about his head, nodding as he passed the night guard within the hall. <br>
<br>
He made his way toward the stairs, but continued past. Upstairs was the room of the “guild boss”, at least, as the rest of the guild riffraff knew him as. The shadow knew the front for what it was, a protective shield for the darker secret held deeper within. He continued down the first hall, finding the very common looking spiral stairwell leading below the guild house’s street level structure. The shadow descended the stairs, emerging below to an empty room with one door before him. Knowing by now that he had no choice but to continue the course, he did not hesitate in the slightest as he walked towards it, reaching out to open the door. <br>
<br>
The door opened before his hand even touched the knob. <br>
<br>
Expecting nothing less, the shadow strode calmly into the chamber. The room before him was large and lit by candles from across the room. Sitting in a very comfortable looking throne was a particularly bored looking elf, her chin resting in one hand as she reclined against one side of the throne. <br>
<br>
“Poor, poor Saiioth,” she purred, “haven’t we been over this once already? Need I show you the futility of standing against me yet again?” <br>
<br>
The bored expression was replaced with one much more sinister, as her eyes focused much more sharply on the young elf before her. <br>
<br>
“It’s unfortunate that things will have to end this way,” she continued. “You showed a lot of promise, and yet your attempts at betrayal, though quaint and flattering at first, have now become a nuisance. I’m sure even you can realize how this must end, after your last pitiful display of deception.” <br>
<br>
She rose gracefully, regally, her robes flowing about her as she raised her staff before her, the first, and last, spell she needed to strike down this fool before her already on her lips. <br>
<br>
“Have you anything to say, foolish, pitiful, poor, poor Saiioth?” she purred again, “or will you admit your failure, your defeat, your pathetic insistence of seeking a death at my hands?” <br>
<br>
Saiioth glanced up from tugging absently at one of his gloves, infuriating the mage with the look of boredom sincerely on his own face. He raised his arms out; hands extended upward and shrugged, shaking his head from side to side, his gaze looking down once more as he sighed with remorse <br>
<br>
“I see your point. All things being equal, I can’t see how this can possibly turn out any different than our last meeting...” <br>
<br>
The young rogue’s head slowly rose, meeting the gaze of the elven mentalist. The mentalist had overwhelmed many foes before, savoring their look of despair, of terror, as the realization that their time of reckoning was upon them. So it was with a sincere anticipation that she waiting to see the look upon this worthless, brash, boastful young elf, to see him swallow his pride in the last few moments of his useless life. <br>
<br>
It was with sincere disappointment and seething hatred that that anticipation was replaced, as Saiioth smirked. <br>
