<br>
Saiioth watched the sun rise, just as he had done every day for the past month. He sighed quietly, looking at his unused bed. Even though he had yet to remember, to glimpse the cause of his many sleepless nights, he knew it to be the same nightmare. Since returning to Tir na Nog one month ago, he had been plagued with restless nights and listless days, each brief moment between sleep and wakefulness leaving him with the same vague feeling. <br>
<br>
That feeling was one of pure terror, casting off any idea of returning to sleep. He could not remember upon waking what would cause such emotion, only that it was something to be feared, to be avoided. <br>
<br>
To be left alone. <br>
<br>
Saiioth stretched and decided to travel into the merchant bazaar today, just like every other day. He could not help but smirk as he looked down at the collection of herbs, incense, and sleeping potions he had already purchased, each and every one proven useless. The few merchants who dealt such novelties had come to know Saiioth, or more importantly, Saiioth’s money. They would surely have yet another miracle cure for him to try tonight. <br>
<br>
Saiioth found the city quiet this morning. A few craftsmen and merchants were about, setting up their businesses and chatting amongst themselves. He realized that it might be a few hours before many were open for business, so he decided to visit the tavern, in hopes of finding something fresh to eat this morning. <br>
<br>
As he turned the corner leading out of the merchant bazaar, Saiioth ran directing into a young man, knocking him down. <br>
<br>
The man looked up, a slow smile coming over his face. Glancing from side to side, he rose and leaned toward Saiioth. <br>
<br>
“Good morn to you, kind sir. Say, could you spare a few gold for a man who’s found a bit of poverty?” <br>
<br>
The man peered oddly into the rogue’s eyes, watching him closely. Saiioth felt a bit dazed, hazy from his lack of sleep and the shock of bumping into the man. Numbly, he reached down, untying the strings to his coin pouch. <br>
<br>
“Here now, no need for all the trouble, good sir. Why not just give me the whole pouch?” the man said, calmly, reaching out a hand towards the purse. <br>
<br>
Saiioth nodded, placing the pouch into the awaiting hand. Without another word, the man turned away, walking briskly to the nearest alleyway. <br>
<br>
Moments later, Saiioth shook his head and glanced down where his coin purse should be. He went over the events that just took place, replaying them again and again in his mind. Even with his lack of sleep, and haziness that suspiciously seemed to now be gone, Saiioth could only come to one conclusion. <br>
<br>
He had just been robbed. <br>
<br>
___________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
Saiioth stood within the alley’s shadow, and watched the girl walk into the building just across the street. It had been the fourth thief he had watched accept a “donation” from an unsuspecting traveler, and the fourth thief who then returned to this building. <br>
<br>
Saiioth held a hand to his head, trying to think through his afternoon headache. They always came around this time, which normally found him lying awake in his bed with the curtains drawn. Instead, he was out in the city - the very bright city - trying to concentrate beyond the pain and make sense of what he was now seeing. <br>
<br>
The building was quite familiar to the rogue. He had personally exposed the guildmaster as a spy against Hibernia, ruining his reputation amongst thieves, and forcing him to flee from the authorities. By affiliation, the guildhall itself suffered, and was closed down shortly thereafter. <br>
<br>
Except that now, it appeared to be still operating. <br>
<br>
He looked up, hearing the door from the guildhall opening. Out stepped two very well equipped guards. They turned, heading directly for where he was hiding. Saiioth flinched, looking about to make sure that his location could not be spotted from that far away. Regardless of the implausibility of being discovered, Saiioth slinked back, turning to leave. <br>
<br>
He stopped short, staring in disbelief at the robed woman who stood calmly before him. With a disarming smile, she motioned towards the guildhall as the approaching guards escorted him inside. <br>
<br>
____________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
Saiioth was brought into a large room, candles from across the other side providing light. There before him stood a woman, bent over a table reading various scrolls with interest. As he and his escort entered, she looked up. As she dismissed the guards with a wave, Saiioth studied his hostess. <br>
<br>
She was an elf, on the young side of middle age, though it appeared she had not lost much of her youthful looks. Her hair was white, but it retained its vibrant shine. She was dressed in very exquisite clothing, both expensive and comfortable looking. He noticed as well that although the guards had left, the robed woman who confronted him in the alley was still by the door. <br>
<br>
His hostess turned to regard him, an amused smile on her face. “Welcome, fair rogue, to my guildhall. I think you will find a few things have changed since you were last here.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth bowed, saying “I fear you have me at a disadvantage. For you obviously know who I am, and yet, I’ve never had the pleasure of your acquaintance.” <br>
<br>
The hostess nodded, seeming pleased. “I am Elzadaeli, guildmistress of this hall. How may I be of service?” <br>
<br>
Saiioth responded, “It seems one of your guildmembers had mistaken me for a common mark, and made off with my coin purse. I understand that this is what a thief does, so I will not insult you by asking for it to be returned. Instead, I will simply inform you that I will retrieve the amount owed me from the man himself.” <br>
<br>
As he finished speaking, the robed woman moved forward and handed Saiioth his coin purse. The rogue took it, conscious of the fact that it was quite heavier than when he parted with in. <br>
<br>
He bowed to the guildmistress, “Thank you, Guildmistress Elzadaeli, for this gesture of honor. Tell me, to what do I owe the excess coin?” <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli purred, “Perhaps I hope to gain favor with one as skilled as you, Master Saiioth. I have need for one of your talents, and would pay handsomely for them.” <br>
<br>
She raised a hand as Saiioth made to speak, “Come now, I have spent too much of your time already. Please, enjoy my hospitality, and we will discuss this more in the morning. I’ve your room prepared already, and I think you will find it to your liking.” <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli returned to the scrolls on the table before her, assuming the discussion was over. The robed woman bade Saiioth to follow her. She led him to his room, allowing him to refresh himself, and later brought him to the dining hall. <br>
<br>
Later that night, after a very good meal, Saiioth found himself alone at last in the guest room prepared for him. He lay back on the bed, exhausted from the long day’s activities, and closed his eyes. <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s eyes opened to the sound of birds chirping. With a start, he realized that the light pouring through the window was from the noonday sun. Subconsciously, he brought a hand to his head, slowly becoming aware of the lack of pain, of tiredness. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli greeted him with a smile as he was led into her room later that afternoon. Her smile grew wider as Saiioth asked slyly, “So tell me, which of my talents you were interested in, exactly?” <br>
