<br>
Saiioth sat in the commons room, enjoying his morning meal. The past months had been rather enjoyable, finding both a reprieve from his sleepless nights, as well as making a fair sum of money. He nodded to the friendly gestures of those coming in from a long night’s work, many of them looking up to the elf who had worked his way into a prominent position within the rogue guild so quickly. There was no animosity, no jealousy coming from those who worked for the guild. Everyone profited equally, regardless of their role, from those that worked the streets, those who smuggled supplies into the guildhall, even to Saiioth who had become Elzadaeli’s senior enforcer. <br>
<br>
He had to admit the respect he saw in each of their eyes was worth more than all the money he stood to make from this agreement. <br>
<br>
Saiioth smiled as he looked about the room. It didn’t take long for one to see just how effective a guild Elzadaeli ran. Street thieves and mentalists worked in tandem, befuddling their marks and walking away with full coin purses. Assassins and enchanters would stalk their prey, magically holding them in place for the perfect enchanted strike, only to elude detection by running away with enchanted speed. <br>
<br>
He glanced up at the woman who sat down at his table, idly reading a scroll of the day’s assignments. They had been assigned together since his first day at the guild, and had progressed quickly into becoming the most respected pair here. They were now the guild’s official “emissaries”, which was a fancy way of saying they made visits to those who didn’t see things the guild’s way to convince them otherwise. <br>
<br>
She normally wore plain brown traveling robes, like the ones she wore when she confronted Saiioth in the alleyway at their first meeting. He noted that she was wearing her audience robes today, quite radiant and charming. He was almost positive they had an enchantment about them to increase just that emotion. Her dark violet hair was pulled back and braided intricately. It was apparent they had an important visit to make today, as Saiioth knew the mentalist before him despised dressing up this much. <br>
<br>
He was about to ask as much, when a figure entered through the front door. At first, he was a little intrigued that such a young boy would be seen walking into a rogue’s guild, but something stirred within his heart, as recognition knocked quietly in the recesses of his mind. <br>
<br>
Kaejar. <br>
<br>
The little lurikeen boy walked through the room, apparently knowing where he was going, and looking every part of belonging there. Saiioth’s partner glanced up, a questioning look on her face as she noticed both the boy and Saiioth’s stare. <br>
<br>
“Something wrong, Saiioth?” <br>
<br>
“Huh? Oh, no…nothing. I just…thought I knew that boy.” <br>
<br>
The woman nodded, returning to her paperwork, “He’s fairly new here, but you might have seen him around I guess.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth shook his head, “No, that’s not it. I know that boy from my hometown. He’s from Ardee, but he’s no thief. There must be some mistake.” <br>
<br>
The mentalist looked up again, taking notice of Saiioth’s growing agitation. Putting aside the scroll in front of her, she asked him plainly, “Why is that?” <br>
<br>
“Because he’s just a boy. He doesn’t belong here. He shouldn’t BE here!” Saiioth said, growing more and more concerned. <br>
<br>
The woman sighed, saying, “I guess we need to go talk to Lady Elzadaeli. It’s obvious you’re not going to let this just drop. For your own good, you better hear what she has to say about it.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth nodded grimly. He was sure Elzadaeli would understand. <br>
<br>
________________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
“Who?” Elzadaeli said, with the same bored tone she produced the first two times she asked. <br>
<br>
“Kaejar. Young lurikeen boy from Ardee,” Saiioth said, his patience nearing its limit. <br>
<br>
“Ah right,” Elzadaeli said, with very little conviction. “And what is the trouble with the boy?” <br>
<br>
“He doesn’t belong here. I don’t think he should be a part of the guild,” Saiioth said, with a little more emotion then he wanted to use. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli sat quietly for a moment, letting the words hang in the air briefly. <br>
<br>
“I disagree.” <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli turned back to her work at the table. Saiioth did not move to leave. <br>
<br>
“Surely he can not be that important to our guild? There can’t be that much of a need for a mere boy to play a role?” <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli stared at Saiioth, a look of annoyance at being interrupted from her work. <br>
<br>
“He plays a vital role, just like everyone in this guild. There are many benefits to having an “innocent” child about, the most obvious being their ability to get close to a target without them being suspect.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth tried hard from keeping his mouth from dropping open as the meaning of her words became clear. Using children for petty pick pocketing was one thing, but this? <br>
<br>
“Surely you wouldn’t put a child in harm’s way?” <br>
<br>
“How do you think we came to need “another” child assassin?” she retorted. Saiioth thought he detected a slight edge of amusement to her voice. He felt his body grow cold. <br>
<br>
“But you said that everyone is vital to the guild-“ <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli cut him off. “I said he plays a vital ROLE, Saiioth. Just like everyone here. Everyone knows the danger associated with his or her rank. They know that, if they fall, they can be replaced with another, whether that other be a young apprentice mentalist, a mercenary assassin, or even another worthless lurikeen street urchin.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth stared, unblinking. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli held the stare for a long time. Finally, she said, “I do believe you have an important meeting to attend, Saiioth. I would hate to see you miss it.” <br>
<br>
With that, Elzadaeli turned to her worktable, focusing at the work at hand and forgetting about their discussion. <br>
<br>
Saiioth left, knowing that he had work to focus on as well, but could not forget their conversation. <br>
<br>
He would not forget. <br>
