<br>
Saiioth sat in his room, fuming. He had returned from his most recent job, a contact in Lough Gur who had not been as forthcoming with guild funds as he now knew he should be, to watch Kaejar walk calmly through the commons room. <br>
<br>
With a bloody dirk hanging from his belt. <br>
<br>
He knew he had already decided what he had to do. Even if he were able to get Kaejar away from the guild, he would have to deal with Elzadaeli chasing after them, or at the least, recruiting more children for such dirty work. <br>
<br>
Saiioth could not allow himself to be a party to that. <br>
<br>
As night fell in the city of Tir na Nog, Saiioth strapped on his blades, and waited quietly in the darkness of his room for the dead of night. <br>
__________________________________________________________________________ <br>
<br>
He made his way down to the lower floors, staying within the shadows and avoiding the few other guildmembers who were awake this late at night. He found it rather surprising that he encountered no guards, but was not about to question his good fortune. He found the door to Elzadaeli’s room easily enough. <br>
<br>
Saiioth heard a sound from above the stairs, heading down. Without concern, he moved into position, just inside the shadows, but close enough to the door to slip in should this person open the door ahead of him. The guard entered Elzadaeli’s room, with Saiioth diving quietly inside. The shadows were not long, and the rogue held his breath, crouching perfectly still. He knew he would have trouble if he made a move while the guard was in the room as well, but if he came to be discovered, he would be sure to get the first strike. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli was pouring over a series of reports on the table. She took the guard’s report with little word, just a wave of the hand, and the guard promptly let her be, leaving her room alone. <br>
<br>
Alone for Saiioth. <br>
<br>
He stalked into position, finding a place to make his strike from behind. Gathering himself for one quick run, he crouched down, and leapt forward. <br>
<br>
Aided by his magical bracers, he moved exceptionally fast, even for an elf. As he closed the distance, still silent, Elzadaeli spun around in alarm. <br>
<br>
She raised her hands, as if to stop the blade’s advance. Already within striking range, Saiioth easily avoided the meager defenses, aiming his blade for a quick, deadly stab. <br>
<br>
He felt the blade strike something material. Forcibly, the blade was turned aside, as if Elzadaeli were wearing a suit of scale armor. Saiioth could not slow down his approach, and stumbled forward from the unexpected deflection. <br>
<br>
Into Elzadaeli’s hands. <br>
<br>
With both hands, she grabbed the rogue’s vest. Calmly, as if fully prepared for such a fortuitous situation, she shouted the incantation. An enormous blast propelled Saiioth across the room and into the wall, where he crumpled to the floor. <br>
<br>
He stood groggily, attempting to raise his weapons in a defense. He looked down to see his arms hanging limply at his sides. He strained to gain control of his arms, but could only watch futilely as his grip lessened, dropping the blades to the floor. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli’s laughter rang in his ears as she calmly walked forward to the rogue, shaking her head. <br>
<br>
“I take you in, I bring peace to your mind, I pay you handsomely for performing the most simple of tasks, and this is how you repay me?” she asked sweetly. <br>
<br>
Saiioth could only return her gaze. <br>
<br>
“Do you honestly think you are the first rogue to EVER try and bring about my demise?” she purred. “Oh poor Saiioth, you have a lot to learn.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth felt his body returning to his control. He bent down, swiftly recovering his blades, and ran towards Elzadaeli. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli only smiled. <br>
<br>
Saiioth raised his blades to strike, but as he came closer, he slowed. He began to feel an overwhelming sense of dread, of hopelessness, centering on the idea of striking down the woman before him. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli laughed in his face. <br>
<br>
The turmoil in his mind was too strong. He stared at Elzadaeli, his greatest desire to strike her dead causing him intense mental pain. He knew beyond a doubt that to do so would be followed with his own death, caused by his own mind being overwhelmed by the mental anguish his brain was associating with the idea of causing harm to this elf. <br>
<br>
Tauntingly, Elzadaeli spread her arms wide, giving Saiioth a clean shot. <br>
<br>
Saiioth threw the blades down, disgusted. Elzadaeli nodded, and walked back to her throne. <br>
<br>
“You see, don’t you poor Saiioth? You have no chance against me. There is no point in following this any further. I hope you will now put away such foolish thoughts of harming me, and return to your work.” <br>
<br>
“My work?” Saiioth asked, astounded. <br>
<br>
“Of course. I understand your rebellion. You just haven’t had time to see things clearly. You’re a very capable servant, one that I would like to keep around. Do not give me any reason to doubt you, and you can remain here, working for me, finding escape from your ‘mental condition’,” she said with a sly smile to Saiioth’s shocked face, “and be well paid for your services.” <br>
<br>
“And I suppose if I refuse, you will strike me dead here and now?” Saiioth reasoned. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli shook her head. <br>
<br>
“Of course not. Such a threat would have no effect on a man who has looked death in the face. No, I will not kill you.” <br>
<br>
Then, too calmly, she stated, “Instead, I will kill Kaejar.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s head spun, trying to think of any alternative he could. He cursed under his breath as he became aware of the fact that Elzadaeli was already reading his mind. <br>
<br>
“And if you try to leave, not only will I KNOW you plan to leave before you try, I will kill Kaejar…. <br>
<br>
“By your own hand.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth slumped, feeling defeated. He turned to leave, sickened by the complete failure of his attack, of giving up Kaejar to such a life of vileness, and by the condescending laughter that followed him out of Elzadaeli’s chambers. The laughter rattled inside of his ears all the way back to his room, and stayed with him throughout the night. <br>
<br>
For once in the past months, Saiioth did not sleep well. <br>
