<br>
Saiioth sat in his room, where he had remained for the past few days. His equipment was left in a pile on the floor, sitting across the room and out of reach. <br>
<br>
Saiioth barely gave it a second look. <br>
<br>
He had no pressing business. Elzadaeli had purposely given him some time off, to ponder and fully realize how hopeless any retaliation would be against her. Leaving the room only to eat, Saiioth spent another evening alone with his thoughts. <br>
<br>
Saiioth smirked while thinking about that just now. His thoughts weren’t even his own anymore. Every intricate plot, every conceived idea of combating the guildmaster was second guessed, destroyed by doubt, and ultimately given up on. There was no hope in planning when those plans would be so easily seen through, even as they were written up within Saiioth’s own mind. <br>
<br>
His head turned at the slight knock at his door. Even before he could respond, the door opened. In slipped the woman in robes, his assigned partner. She quickly closed the door behind her, and turned to regard the rogue. <br>
<br>
“What is the meaning of this?” the elf asked. <br>
<br>
The woman raised a finger to her lips, removing an ornate candleholder from a fold in her robes. The candle’s design was a swirling pattern of black and white wax. Without a word, the elven mage lit the candle, placing it on a nightstand next to the rogue’s bed. <br>
<br>
Saiioth watched carefully, not completely trusting his “partner” after all that had occurred within the guild’s walls. <br>
<br>
“I’ll ask only once more. What is the meaning of this?” <br>
<br>
“I came to see how you were doing. It’s been a few days since your….altercation with Lady Elzadaeli. I had hoped you would not seem so defeated,” she said, looking over the elven rogue. <br>
<br>
Saiioth looked suspiciously at the woman. “I don’t know what you’re talking about.” <br>
<br>
The woman chuckled, but quickly grew serious. “Saiioth, we don’t have much time. Let’s speak bluntly.” <br>
<br>
She noticed him glance over at the candle sitting beside him. <br>
<br>
“The candle is magical in nature. It envelops this room, protecting from prying ears and minds. Any who attempt to delve into the room will be met with a jumble of…amorous feelings and emotions,” she ended, looking pointedly away from the rogue. <br>
<br>
“I beg your pardon?” the rogue asked, raising an eyebrow. <br>
<br>
“Look, we don’t have a lot of time,” she said, returning her eyes to his once more. “I came to see if you were still determined to defeat the guildmaster.” <br>
<br>
The robed woman scowled at the sigh that escaped the rogue. <br>
<br>
“Of course I am! I must!” the rogue began, before losing his spirit. “But I just can’t see any way around her magical edge in this battle….” the rogue said, then just shook his head and shrugged. <br>
<br>
The woman stood before him, her arms crossed with one finger tapping, lost in thought. <br>
<br>
“Perhaps I can help, but only if you think you’re up for the challenge.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth looked up, a slight glimmer returning to his eyes. “Go on.” <br>
<br>
The woman shrugged, “I know of a man who it is said knows more about Lady Elzadaeli than any person. In his possession are many tombs of knowledge and items of magical power. He once worked for Lady Elzadaeli, but has since become a recluse. Only those seeking his treasures visit him now, though none have ever returned. The man was always a trickster, so I assume it is not pure coincidence. Your life might be your only bargaining item as well, but then again, it will be a gamble just leaving the guildhall for more than a day. <br>
<br>
“Of course, the moment you leave this room, Lady Elzadaeli will surely know your plans. Stepping outside of the hall will be the end of your life, and that of your friend, young Kaejar.” <br>
<br>
“So what do you propose?” asked the rogue, looking for guidance from the elven mage. <br>
<br>
“I know how to reach the trickster, and I could get you there by tomorrow morning. You would have to return by the following day. That would be as long as I could cover for your disappearance. All that leaves is how to get you past Lady Elzadaeli’s mental alarms,” she said. <br>
<br>
Saiioth looked to his equipment, piled up on the floor. His eyes stopped on the bracer. <br>
<br>
“Tell me, could you carry my body from this room and to the trickster’s location?” <br>
<br>
The woman followed his gaze, a slow smile crossing her face as she gathered the basics of his plan. <br>
<br>
“I could provide such means, yes. How long will the poison last? Should you wake up before clearing Lady Elzadaeli’s mental range-” <br>
<br>
Saiioth raised a hand, his eyes showing resolve once more. <br>
<br>
“I trust my poisons enough to place my life in their hands. Get me to the trickster, and I will surely return in time,” the rogue replied. “But, tell me, why do you risk involvement to help me?” <br>
<br>
The woman looked away, her eyes subconsciously drawn to the candle’s flame. <br>
<br>
“Though you might not be aware, there are reasons why such an obvious charade provided by the candle’s magic would be accepted by the guildhall’s members,” she said, her voice growing quiet. “Perhaps when you return, they could be discussed more in detail.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s eyes widened, but before he could respond, he found his bracer thrown to where he was sitting. <br>
<br>
“But for now, troubled rogue, there is business to tend to. We do not have much time,” she said, her voice once again strong and emotionless. <br>
<br>
The rogue removed the proper needle, poisoned and prepared. He looked up at the woman before him. <br>
<br>
“Thank you for doing so much for so little,” he said, pricking his finger with the needle and lying back on the bed. <br>
<br>
The rogue considered the woman’s smile that followed him into unconsciousness. His instincts grasped desperately for control of his quieting mind, not quite sure of the sincerity or integrity of that Cheshire grin, but ultimately losing to the power of his sleeping poison. <br>
