<br>
Saiioth awoke to find the stars fading from sight above him. The rogue rolled over to find himself lying in an open field. He stood up and brushed himself off, trying to get a sense of his surroundings. <br>
<br>
“Ah, now that you’re awake, what do you think you’re doing here?” <br>
<br>
Saiioth turned towards the sudden voice. Standing before a weathered hut was an old man, staring at him. He did not look very happy to find the rogue sleeping in front of him home. <br>
<br>
“I do believe I’m looking for you, good sir,” the rogue responded. <br>
<br>
“Well, then you’re mistaken,” the man called out. “I’m certainly not a ‘good sir’.” <br>
<br>
With that the man turned and entered his small home, though he did not stop to close the door. Having no other option, Saiioth approached and entered the hut. As he stepped through the doorway, the door closed silently behind him. <br>
<br>
A bright chandelier suddenly illuminated the room, and the rogue found himself standing in a huge foyer. Surprised, he looked about the room, turning back to find the ornate door closed solidly behind him. The old man entered from an adjoining room then, with a carafe and two glasses. <br>
<br>
“Well then, perhaps I am the man you are looking for after all. I assume you’ve come to challenge me like all the others?” he said, a bit of mirth now entering his voice. <br>
<br>
Saiioth nodded, still glancing about the enormous room. <br>
<br>
“Come my boy, have a seat. I know, it takes a little getting used to, but you don’t think a man of my stature would waste away my last years in a little stone hut, do you? Now, let’s get on to business. I’m a very busy man, you know.” <br>
<br>
The old man poured two glasses of a dark violet wine. Setting a glass before the rogue, he sat in a chair and sipped thoughtfully. Saiioth took the glass carefully, sniffing the contents. Noticing the chuckle from his host, he decided that this day would be filled with chances, and took a sip from his own glass. <br>
<br>
“You assume much, sir, but let’s continue with that thought then. Suppose I have come to challenge you. What would I challenge you for?” <br>
<br>
The old man smiled, “A sly one, eh? They all think themselves pretty witty before the battle begins. Young man, as you can probably surmise from my very home, I am a man of many magical artifacts. And beyond the mundane and not so mundane trinkets that I own, I have an extensive library. Any object from my personal treasure is yours, should you defeat me. You have my word. <br>
<br>
“However, should I win, you must forfeit your magical items to me. In the event that you do not have any thing worth taking, then you must forfeit your freedom. Judging from your profession and equipment, I can already see that it will have to be the latter for you,” he finished. <br>
<br>
The rogue smiled, judging the old man standing before him as well. He wore fancy leather riding clothes; like aristocrats wore when taking their noonday horse rides. The man had no weapons visible on his person, and certainly did not appear to be ready for any type of battle. <br>
<br>
“I assume we are talking about something other than sword fighting,” the rogue said with a smirk. <br>
<br>
“Very perceptive, young man,” the man smiled, “we will in fact be playing a different type of battle. One I’ve imported from the far foreign lands.” <br>
<br>
He motioned then to a small table, made up entirely of a checkered top. On it’s surface were two lines of figurines, of different heights and shapes. <br>
<br>
“Course, it would be unfair to expect you to know the rules, so I’ll be sure to tell you when you play a foul,” the man began, grinning. <br>
<br>
“I know the game of chess. From Albion, correct?” the rogue smirked. <br>
<br>
“You’ve heard of it?” the old man asked, looking a little deflated. “Well, then perhaps I’ll finally have a challenge. It will be rather entertaining to play someone other than these classless country bumpkins I normally get wandering into my home.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth sat at the table, looking over the pieces carefully. The old man sat down across from him, still sipping his glass of wine. <br>
<br>
“I believe that I go first, correct?” the rogue inquired. <br>
<br>
“Indeed, lad. Be my guest,” smiled the old man. <br>
<br>
Saiioth moved a piece forward. He had read a few books on basic rules and strategy, but had not actually played a game against someone before. He decided to play defensively first, and see where the old man led the game. <br>
<br>
Seven moves later, the old man smiled and said, “Checkmate.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth stared at the board in disbelief. <br>
<br>
“That’s impossible,” Saiioth exclaimed with conviction. “How did you do that?” <br>
<br>
The old man cackled, “Simple lad, because I read your mind.” He raised his hands before the rogue, showing a richly embroidered pair of pale blue leather gloves, with gold stitching. “It wouldn’t matter if you were the best player in the world, you had no chance to win from the beginning!” <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s eyes narrowed as the old man continued to laugh heartily. <br>
<br>
“Play me again.” <br>
<br>
“I’m sorry boy, did you say something?” the man laughed. <br>
<br>
“Play me again.” <br>
<br>
“Lad, don’t take it so hard, everyone loses. There’s no chance to beat me, besides which, you’ve nothing noteworthy to stake another game on.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s smile calmed the old man, and piqued his interest. “Oh, I think I do. I’m sure you’ll think right away that I’m bluffing, so go ahead, read my mind,” Saiioth said, calmly closing his eyes and picturing the book stored safely in his personal room back in Tir na Nog. <br>
<br>
The old man tapped his hands thoughtfully. “Okay lad, we’ll give it another go. If I win, I still get your life, but not before you hand over that book.” <br>
<br>
“And if I win, old man, you give me back my freedom, plus the original stake in the first game. Otherwise, no deal,” Saiioth announced, a smirk on his face. <br>
<br>
“It’s not like you can’t read my mind,” he said, in answer to the old man’s trepidation. <br>
<br>
“Okay lad, you’re on!” the old man said, laughing once more, “You’ve got no chance of beating me anyway.” <br>
<br>
The old man’s laughter trailed off to silence at the look on Saiioth’s face. The old man’s fears were realized when Saiioth spoke again. <br>
<br>
“So, what are the rules to the game?” <br>
<br>
The old man began with a slight sigh of relief, “Well lad, each piece has a certain move-“ <br>
<br>
“No, old man,” Saiioth interrupted, “not that game.” <br>
<br>
The old man grew quiet, a look of concern on his face. <br>
<br>
“That’s right. There’s more than one game going on here. Isn’t it odd, that a man with such an advantage would so clearly give it away at the first question? Even when it was so general that one could clearly lie about it? And isn’t it odd that during our first game, you declined to provide the rules to the chess match, yet with but one request you’re prepared to tell me, even when I told you I know how to play the game? <br>
<br>
“So, old man, what are the rules to the game, not including this chess board before us?” <br>
<br>
The old man sighed, and then replied, “There is only one rule. Any question that you ask, I must answer truthfully. <br>
<br>
“Not that it matters, because I can still read your mind,” the old man finished, grinning once more. <br>
<br>
Saiioth studied the board, preparing for his first move. Even as his hand came down to grasp a piece, he looked up at the old man across the table. Placing the piece down and completing his move, he asked, “Tell me, what’s the capital of our fair land, Hibernia?” <br>
<br>
The old man looked vaguely confused, but shook his head and answered, “Such a silly question boy. It’s Tir na Nog.” The old man then completed his own turn. <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s eyes never left the old man, as his hand’s continued to work the board, each move followed by another question. The old man answered them all, continuing to keep up with his opponent’s movements on the board as well. <br>
<br>
“What gets harder to catch the faster you run?” <br>
<br>
“Your breath.” <br>
<br>
“What belongs to you but others use it more than you do?” <br>
<br>
“Your name.” <br>
<br>
“At night they come without being fetched, and by day they are lost without being stolen. What are they?” <br>
<br>
“The stars.” <br>
<br>
And so the questions and riddles continued, matched breath for breath and move for move. Saiioth forced the game faster, but was paced easily by the wise old man. Finally, Saiioth thought he had stumped the old man. <br>
<br>
“You are walking down a road and you come to a fork in the path. You look ahead to see two gates, one on each separate path. In front of both of these gates stands one guard. You've heard of this place before, and you know that one guard will lie to you, and one guard will tell you the truth, but you aren't sure which one is which. If you had to ask one of them one question to figure out which way to go, which person would you ask, and what would you ask them?” <br>
<br>
The old man pondered the question for a long time. Finally, he made his move on the board, answering the question with conviction and calm. <br>
<br>
“You would go up to either one of them, it doesn't matter which one, and say ‘If I were to ask the other guard which way to go, what would he say?’ and whichever gate that person points to, go the opposite way. Pretend for one moment that it is the Truth person you are talking to. He knows that the other one will lie and tell you to go a certain way so they will point that direction and you know that is the wrong way to go, so you go the opposite. But if it was the Liar that you were talking to, he knows that the other guard will tell you the right way to go, but the Liar wouldn't tell you that he will lie, so he will point opposite of what he knows is true...either way you go opposite,” the old man replied, nodding his head with assurance. <br>
<br>
Saiioth smiled, clapping at the old man’s ability. “Well done, good sir!” <br>
<br>
With that, he reached down, to make his next move. Looking up with a smirk, Saiioth announced, “Checkmate.” <br>
<br>
The old man stared with quiet shock at the simplicity of the trap he had walked into, both on the board and within the conversation. With a sigh, he laid down the king. <br>
<br>
“So there you have it,” Saiioth said, “our battle comes to an end. Now then, I do believe the prize was my freedom, and one of your many artifacts of my choosing?” <br>
<br>
The old man nodded numbly, having refocused on the young rogue; he already knew the object that had gained Saiioth’s affections. <br>
<br>
“Hand over the gloves, and I will take my leave, good sir,” Saiioth said, “For I have pressing business to attend to.” <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#A0B0E0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tylvillenria>Tyl Villenria</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#3333ff>(7/30/03 4:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fkelrycksdaocradioandroleplaycenterfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=177.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Chased by Shadows</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>**Chased by Shadows** Chapter 7: Midnight/Morning – Emotionless</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
“Have you anything to say, foolish, pitiful, poor, poor Saiioth?” she purred again, “or will you admit your failure, your defeat, your pathetic insistence of seeking a death at my hands?” <br>
<br>
Saiioth glanced up from tugging absently at one of his gloves, infuriating the mage with the look of boredom sincerely on his own face. He raised his arms out; hands extended upward and shrugged, shaking his head from side to side, his gaze looking down once more as he sighed with remorse <br>
<br>
“I see your point. All things being equal, I can’t see how this can possibly turn out any different than our last meeting...” <br>
<br>
The young rogue’s head slowly rose, meeting the gaze of the elven mentalist. The mentalist had overwhelmed many foes before, savoring their look of despair, of terror, as the realization that their time of reckoning was upon them. So it was with a sincere anticipation that she waiting to see the look upon this worthless, brash, boastful young elf, to see him swallow his pride in the last few moments of his useless life. <br>
<br>
It was with sincere disappointment and seething hatred that that anticipation was replaced, as Saiioth smirked. <br>
<br>
“But then, how could I return to such a gracious audience without a gift?” <br>
<br>
Saiioth reached out with his mind, his hand unconsciously stretching forth as well, searching for the mental influences that were the defenses of this room. He quickly found what he was looking for, the mental blanket that made drawing a weapon against Elzadaeli a painful thought. In his mind, he could see the spell, entwined about the room’s walls like a string. He envisioned a sharp edged blade, and his mind gave it shape and form in the mental realm. With a quick slash, the string fell away, dropping the field that restricted such movement. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli sensed that a spell had been removed, only to have it confirmed by the unsheathing of Saiioth’s very material blades. The blades whirled in his eager hands, as he slowly stalked forward, eyes never leaving the mentalist. <br>
<br>
His advance slowed considerably when Elzadaeli returned to her throne, a smile playing on her lips. She motioned to her right, presenting an opening door to Saiioth. As the door’s creaking finally ended, out walked a boy, adorned in battle armor and wielding two glowing blades. <br>
<br>
Saiioth’s blades slowly lowered as Kaejar approached. He glanced back to Elzadaeli, whose eyes were closed in concentration. The elf studied Kaejar again, noticing the blank look the young lurikeen boy could not shake. It was clear that he was under her control, yet Saiioth dared not engage in battle with the child for fear of seriously wounding him. <br>
<br>
The elf snapped his blades back into their sheaths, closing his eyes as well. He focused all of his strength through the gloves, opening his mind to the room around him. <br>
<br>
Though hazy for a mind untrained in the mental arts, the magical gloves provided enough of a focal point for him to observe the influences clearly, as if they had form and shape. Across the room, Elzadaeli was manipulating Kaejar’s mind and body, her own arms stretching like smoke from her seat. In that seat rose her mind, swaying like a snake’s head as it noticed him awaken in the mental plane. One arm relinquished Kaejar, flying across the room at Saiioth. Purely by reflex, the elf reached out and grappled with the attacking arm, holding it in place in the middle of the room. At the same moment, Elzadaeli’s remaining hand, still holding Kaejar’s mind, raised off the ground, taking Kaejar with her. Below the lurikeen, the ground disappeared into oblivion. Saiioth’s remaining hand, having instinctively moved to prevent the attack by Kaejar’s controlled mind, stopped midway and latched onto the hand holding Kaejar precariously. <br>
<br>
The room was perfectly still, each taking in the current situation in that brief moment. Saiioth realized the implications immediately. With each of them tied up on one side, he could remove his other hand, striking down Elzadaeli instantly. However, in that same instant, Elzadaeli would release Kaejar’s mind, sending it crashing down into the abyss below, causing the lurikeen boy to go into mental shock. And, should he allow her the first move, it would invariably be the same; release of the boy, knowing Saiioth would then rush to save him, leaving himself open to attack. <br>
<br>
Within that moment, Saiioth had made his decision. He released the hand holding Kaejar, moving his hand beneath the child to catch the inevitable drop as Elzadaeli took advantage of the freed arm. <br>
<br>
Elzadaeli’s laughter filled the room as her arm raced forward, aimed to strike Saiioth’s mind. The elf turned away, focusing on catching Kaejar’s mind and getting it to safety. <br>
<br>
The laughter was quickly replaced with a surprised gasp, then a scream of anguish. Saiioth spun around, attempting to make sense of what he saw before him. <br>
<br>
Two arms reached out from the shadows, one grasping the arm Elzadaeli was to use in her attack against Saiioth. The second had wrapped tightly around the mind of Elzadaeli, choking the snake’s head as it made a futile attempt at escaping its hold. <br>
<br>
With both her mental arms held firm, Elzadaeli was defenseless to the newcomer. Saiioth clutched the boy’s mind close and shielded it from the mental screams that emanated from across the room, as Elzadaeli’s mind was attacked by wave after wave of mental energy. The screams grew louder, ringing in Saiioth’s mind, vaguely familiar and stirring within him visions of another horrifying mental attack. Finally, the screams stopped, and the room was silent and still. <br>
<br>
Saiioth looked up and watched with curiosity as the murky mental projections around him slowly dissipated. Quickly, he concentrated on returning to the physical realm, urging his mind to recede to its normal interpretation of his surroundings, as he gently placed Kaejar’s mind and body on the ground before him. <br>
<br>
Standing over the wilted body of Elzadaeli was the woman in robes, a look of detachment on her face. Saiioth walked over, catching their fleeting exchange as Elzadaeli’s last breaths escaped her. <br>
<br>
“N..Naki, how could you do….do this to…me?” Elzadaeli barely uttered, the look of shock on her face following her waning life. <br>
<br>
“It’s just business, mother,” Naki said, her expression unchanged. <br>
<br>
“Nothing personal.” <br>
