<br>
Naki knocked on Saiioth’s door twice, with no answer. Finally, she opened the door, to find the rogue sitting at a table, staring into a mirror. The woman glanced over at his bed, apparently unused. <br>
<br>
“Can’t sleep? The nightmares didn’t come back, did they?” she asked, sincerely concerned. <br>
<br>
The elf looked up, noticing her entrance for the first time. His eyes slowly focused on her standing there, and although it was clear he had not slept at all, a bit of spark returned to those eyes. <br>
<br>
“I’ve had a lot on my mind,” he said, smirking as he raised his hands before him, still wearing the magical leather gloves. <br>
<br>
“Don’t worry about me,” Saiioth continued, the mirth slowly leaving his face. “I’ve discovered my demons, and they will be dealt with in due time.” <br>
<br>
“Speaking of which,” Naki broke in, “I was wondering if you’ve given any more thought to remaining here and working with me. There’s a whole guild here, a lot of responsibility to return it to its former honor.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth smirked at the statement. Partly due to the irony of using the word “honor” when talking about a guild of thieves. The other part was because he was sure the irony was lost on the woman standing before him. <br>
<br>
“I must decline,” he stated. <br>
<br>
Naki nodded, disappointment on her face, though not surprise. “I figured as much. It’s pretty clear you’re not cut out for this type of work.” <br>
<br>
She raised her hands defensively as Saiioth narrowed his eyes, “Not that you’re incapable of doing it, of course. It’s just apparent that your heart is somewhere else.” <br>
<br>
“It is?” he said, genuinely amused. <br>
<br>
“I can understand the chance you took in saving Kaejar. From a business standpoint, he was one of your best contacts,” she mused, “However, even that seems secondary.” <br>
<br>
Saiioth sat quietly, thinking. He became aware of a gentle sensation about his mind, just on the outside, glancing in. Absently, he mentally brushed it aside like a fly. <br>
<br>
Naki hid her interest, even though she knew Saiioth had sensed that it was she. Speaking of Kaejar had led Saiioth to examine his own feelings on the matter, and give the curious woman a glimpse before his defense was in place. It was just the briefest of pictures, more like a vague feeling. Parental? <br>
<br>
Surely there was more to this young elf than he let on. <br>
<br>
“Well, I understand, of course,” she continued, “So you’ve decided to move on. Just don’t hesitate if you ever need our services here. I owe you at least that much. So what are you going to do now?” <br>
<br>
Even though Saiioth had pushed her away mentally just moments ago, even without focusing on him she could sense the anger within him, slowly building towards the surface. Naki unconsciously took a physical step back. <br>
<br>
Saiioth looked up, a smirk playing on his face at the display. Standing up, he gathered his belongings and turned to the door. <br>
<br>
Saiioth stopped in front of Naki as he walked past, his eyes meeting hers, only inches apart. Even though his mind was fully defended now from prying, Naki could see clearly through his eyes down into his very soul. His anger, his hatred, his indignation was so focused, Naki silently told herself to never consider crossing this man, and quietly thanked her good fortune that the advantages she already took with him hadn’t sealed her fate. <br>
<br>
Her body shivered noticeably as she watched him walk down the stairs and leave the guildhall, the single word he whispered as he past, like a secret once told would not dare think of being said aloud again, echoed in her mind: <br>
<br>
“Retribution” <br>
<br>
