<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>She was running through the forest, the edge of the valley in sight. Even though she desperately wanted to return to her home, her beloved home, her gaze continued to be pulled behind her. As if something was there, in the shadows, watching her. Stalking her. <br>
<br>
Finally her legs slowed, and she came to a stop. The feeling was overpowering now, and could not be ignored. She spun around, eyes darting to every shadow of the forest, searching for whatever was hunting her so diligently. <br>
<br>
To her amazement, the wolf walked into the open. It’s body was black as night, it’s eyes golden like stars in the night sky. It’s eyes shone in the moonlight, staring into her eyes, never moving. They stood there together, motionless. <br>
<br>
A cry of alarm rose from the valley behind her. She knew from the panic it caused that her worst fear was coming true, the attack they expected but hoped in vain would never occur, was gripping her beloved home below. She longed to run to them now, to join them in the battle they had prepared for all of their lives, just in case. <br>
<br>
And yet, the wolf transfixed her, its eyes never moving. It continued to stare, watching for a reaction. It seemed oblivious, or at least uncaring, about the commotion behind them, concerned purely with the relation between itself and the woman. <br>
<br>
The cries of alarm quickly changed to yells of fear and pain, and then to death. She knew what was happening, knew there was no hope for her home unless she arrived and rallied her friends and family. She heard the sound of the fires as they consumed the trees, the fields, and the buildings of her home. She heard the fires as they consumed the bodies of her friends and family. <br>
<br>
Yet the wolf continued to hold her still, it’s eyes demanding her attention, judging her silently, as she listened to her village burn to the ground behind her.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <br>
